Breast Cancer Analysis and ML Model¶

Introduction¶

Breast cancer is one of the most common forms of cancer in the world. Some breast cancer statistics from the American Cancer Society include:

  • In 2021, approx. 281,500 new cases of invasive breast cancer will be diagnosed in women.
  • In 2021, approx. 43,600 women will die from breast cancer.
  • Breast cancer is the second leading cause of cancer death in women.
  • The death rate of breast cancer is approx. 1 in 39 (3.6%).

Some quick statistics regarding cancer in general are:

  • In 2018, 12.3% of total cancer cases in the world were from breast cancer (World Cancer Research Fund).
  • In 2018, 25.4% of total cancers in women were from breast cancer (World Cancer Research Fund).

About this Analysis¶

This analysis aims to visually represent breast cancer data, statistically analyze that data, and create a ML model to predict benign or malignant breast tissue based on multiple factors.

print(cancer_data["diagnosis"].unique())

['M' 'B']
In [13]:
diagnosis = []
for i in range(len(cancer_data["diagnosis"])):
    if cancer_data["diagnosis"][i] == "B":
        diagnosis.append(0)
    else:
        diagnosis.append(1)
del cancer_data["diagnosis"]
cancer_data["diagnosis"] = diagnosis

Model Performance¶

Accuracy: 96%

F1 Score (as close to 1 as possible): 0.95

Confusion Matrix:

Here is the complete model as a functioin:

import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.feature_selection import RFE

def cancer_classification(file):
    # Note: `file` is the full path on computer that points to the CSV cancer data.
    cancer_data = pd.read_csv(file)
    # Read NOTE at bottom regarding the code from here till "==="
    diagnosis = []
    for i in range(len(cancer_data["diagnosis"])):
        if cancer_data["diagnosis"][i] == "B":
            diagnosis.append(0)
        else:
            diagnosis.append(1)
    del cancer_data["diagnosis"]
    cancer_data["diagnosis"] = diagnosis
    # ===

    X = cancer_data.drop("diagnosis", axis=1)
    y = cancer_data["diagnosis"]

    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.33, random_state=42)

    rfc = RandomForestClassifier()
    rfe = RFE(estimator=rfc, n_features_to_select=5, step=1)
    rfe = rfe.fit(X_train, y_train)

    return rfe.predict(X_test)

NOTE: The substitution algorithm for diagnosis is included in the function to model all previous steps. In reality, that part should be taken out as there is no diagnosis yet, that is what the model is predicting.

Closing Information¶

Model¶

For the model to work properly, new data should be categorized in the same columns as those of the original data. All columns should be either int64 or float64.
